Reciprocity: Offering a free trial or discount for compliance. A complimentary service package or repair discount might help sell an old clunker. Social exchange theory underlies this method. Social proof: Taking cues from others. Highlighting great customer experiences or presenting testimonials may help sell an old clunker. This method involves normative social influence. Scarcity: Making a product or opportunity scarce to create urgency. Emphasizing that there are few identical automobiles at that price may help sell an ancient junk. Scarcity psychology underlies this method. Authority: Influencing conformity with an authoritative source. Professional examination or certification may help sell an old clunker. Authority governs this strategy's psychology. Scarcity, which generates a feeling of urgency, and Authority, which provides a professional examination or certification, may be more successful at selling an old clunker. 